  <div class="detail-section">
    <h2><i class="fa-solid fa-table-columns"></i> &nbsp;Topic-by-Topic Deep Dive</h2>

    <div class="detail-row">
      <div class="detail-topic">Justification &amp; Salvation</div>
      <div class="detail-col other"><span class="col-label">Protestant</span>Justification = declared righteous before God through faith alone in Christ alone. Works follow salvation as evidence but do not contribute to it. Sanctification (becoming holy) is separate from justification.</div>
      <div class="detail-col lds"><span class="col-label">LDS</span>Universal resurrection (general salvation) is free through Christ. Exaltation (Celestial Kingdom, eternal family, becoming like God) requires faith + repentance + ordinances + covenant faithfulness. Grace and works are inseparable.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="detail-row">
      <div class="detail-topic">Scripture &amp; Authority</div>
      <div class="detail-col other"><span class="col-label">Protestant</span>Bible = 66 books, sole and final authority. Each believer reads and interprets scripture (with guidance). No human institution can add to or override the Bible. The Reformation was about returning to Scripture.</div>
      <div class="detail-col lds"><span class="col-label">LDS</span>Bible + Book of Mormon + D&amp;C + Pearl of Great Price = scripture. Living prophets can receive new revelation that supplements or clarifies all previous scripture. The Church itself is the authoritative interpreter.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="detail-row">
      <div class="detail-topic">Nature of God</div>
      <div class="detail-col other"><span class="col-label">Protestant</span>One God in three co-equal persons (Father, Son, Holy Spirit) of the same divine substance — the Nicene Trinity. God is infinite, eternal, omnipresent spirit with no physical form.</div>
      <div class="detail-col lds"><span class="col-label">LDS</span>God the Father is a glorified, exalted Man with a physical body. Jesus Christ and the Holy Ghost are separate beings. The three are one in purpose, not substance. This Godhead concept was restored, not invented by Nicaea.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="detail-row">
      <div class="detail-topic">Baptism</div>
      <div class="detail-col other"><span class="col-label">Protestant</span>Baptist/Evangelical: believer's baptism by immersion, no saving efficacy — an act of obedience and public profession. Lutheran/Presbyterian: infant baptism, means of grace. Huge variation on meaning and method.</div>
      <div class="detail-col lds"><span class="col-label">LDS</span>Believer's baptism at age 8+ by immersion only. A necessary saving ordinance — not merely symbolic. Performed by Aaronic Priesthood authority. Invalid if not performed by LDS authority.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="detail-row">
      <div class="detail-topic">The Church</div>
      <div class="detail-col other"><span class="col-label">Protestant</span>The Church is the universal body of all true believers ("invisible church"). No single denomination is the one true church. Christians across denominations are united in Christ despite organizational differences.</div>
      <div class="detail-col lds"><span class="col-label">LDS</span>The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints is the only church with the fullness of the gospel and the restored priesthood authority. Other churches have truth but lack the necessary authority to perform saving ordinances.</div>
